'''MV ''Sirius Star''''' is an [[oil tanker]] owned and operated by [[Vela International Marine]].<ref name="CSM">{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/1117/p99s04-duts.html|title=Somali pirates attack tanker loaded with oil|last=McCann|first=Sarah More|date=2008-11-17|publisher=Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=2008-11-17}}</ref>  With a [[length overall]] of {{convert|1090|ft}} and a capacity of {{convert|2000000|oilbbl|m3|lk=on}} of [[crude oil]], the ship is classified as a [[very large crude carrier]] or VLCC.<ref name="CSM"/>  Vela is based in the [[United Arab Emirates]] and is a subsidiary of the [[Saudi Arabian]] state oil company [[Saudi Aramco]].  ''Sirius Star'' is one of Vela's 24 tankers, of which 19 are VLCCs.  Since its launch, the ship has been [[flag state|registered]] under the [[flag of convenience|Liberian flag]] and [[homeport]]ed in [[Monrovia]].<ref name="dnv">{{cite web|url=https://exchange.dnv.com/Exchange/Main.aspx?EXTool=Vessel&VesselID=29210|title=SIRIUS STAR - Summary|publisher=[[Det Norske Veritas]]|accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref>

''Sirius Star'' was built by the [[South Korea]]n company [[Daewoo Shipbuilding & Marine Engineering]].  The ship's construction began in October 2007 and it was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] by Huda M. Ghoson in late March of 2008.<ref name=Vela>{{cite web|url=http://www.vela.ae/news.php?id=61|title=Sirius Star Launching Ceremony |publisher=Vela International|accessdate=2008-11-18}}</ref><ref name="dnv"/>  The launching ceremony was the first in Vela's history that was performed by a Saudi woman.<ref name="vela61"/>

The ship received international attention when it was [[Piracy|hijacked]] by [[Piracy in Somalia|Somali pirates]] on November 15, 2008, becoming the largest ship ever captured by pirates.<ref name="bbc-pirates">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7736472.stm|title=Pirates pass open water test n|last=Walker |first=Robert |date=2008-11-18 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=2008-11-19}}</ref><ref name="largest"/> The ship was ''en route'' from [[Saudi Arabia]] to the [[United States]] by way of the [[Cape of Good Hope]]. At the time of the attack, it was about {{convert|450|nmi|mi km|lk=in}} southeast of the coast of [[Kenya]], carrying 25 crewmen and a full load of oil.  The ship is estimated to be worth approximately [[$US]]&nbsp;148&nbsp;million, the cargo is worth at least $US&nbsp;100&nbsp;million, and 25 hostages are onboard from the Philippines, Poland, Croatia, Great Britain, and Saudi Arabia.

==Design and construction==
''Sirius Star'' is a [[double-hulled tanker|double-hulled]] [[oil tanker]] with a [[length overall]] of {{convert|332|m}}, a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|58|m}}, a hull depth of {{convert|31|m}}, and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|22|m}}.<ref name="dnv"/>  The ship can carry {{convert|2000000|oilbbl|m3|lk=on}} of [[crude oil]].<ref name="dnv"/><ref name="dsme"/>  It has a {{GT|162,252|first=yes}} and a total cargo capacity of {{DWT|318,000|metric|first=yes}}.<ref name="dnv"/>  Vessels of this size are classified as [[Oil tanker#Size categories|very large crude carrier]]s or VLCCs.

The ship was built by [[Daewoo Shipbuilding & Marine Engineering]] (DSME) in [[Okpo]], [[Geoje]], [[South Korea]].  Its [[keel]] was laid on October 29, 2007.<ref name="dnv"/>  Designated as hull number 5302, the ship was the 100th VLCC built by DSME.<ref name="dsme">{{cite journal |author=Lee, Eon-Jeong |date=2008-06-17 |title=Vela Owned H.5302 Marks DSME's 100th |journal=OKPO Gazette |volume=1 |issue=431 |pages=1 |publisher=[[Daewoo Shipbuilding and Marine Engineering]] |location=Okpo, Korea |url=http://www.dsme.co.kr/2004gazette/pdf/431-1.pdf |accessdate=2008-11-19 }}</ref>

''Sirius Star'' was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] by Huda M. Ghoson on March 28, 2008.<ref name=Vela/>  The launch marked the first time a Saudi woman performed such a ceremony for Vela.<ref name="vela61">[http://www.vela.ae/news.php?id=61 Sirius Star Launching Ceremony]. March 28, 2008.</ref>

==Career==

''Sirius Star'' is one of 24 tankers owned and operated by Vela, of which 19 are VLCCs.  Vela, based in the [[United Arab Emirates]] is a subsidiary of the [[Saudi Arabian]] state oil company [[Saudi Aramco]].  Since its launch, the ship has been registered under the [[flag of convenience|Liberian flag]] and homeported in [[Monrovia]].<ref name="dnv"/>

===Hijacking===
